## 3.2 Retrieving data for TensorFlow/Keras models

TensorFlow provides multiple mechanisms to load data efficiently based on
dataset size, model requirements, and performance needs.

---

### 3.2.1 tf.data API

The `tf.data` API offers a scalable and highly configurable pipeline system. It
supports parallel input reading, caching, shuffling, mapping, batching, and
prefetching.

#### Figure 3.7 — End-to-end tf.data pipeline
<p align='left'><img src='./figure/figure3.7.png' width='60%'></p>

---

### 3.2.2 Keras DataGenerators

DataGenerators load images directly from folders and support real-time data
augmentation. They are suitable for medium-sized datasets that do not fit fully
into memory.

---

### 3.2.3 tensorflow-datasets (TFDS)

TFDS offers standardized datasets with automated downloading, extraction,
validation, and built-in train/test splits. It is the quickest way to load
common benchmark datasets.

---

## Summary

Chapter 3 introduced the three Keras APIs (Sequential, Functional, and
Sub-classing) and the three main data-loading mechanisms in TensorFlow
(tf.data, DataGenerators, and TFDS). These tools enable scalable and flexible
deep-learning workflows using TensorFlow 2.
